contentSections.body:
Often you need to check multiple things at once:

**`&&` (AND)** — Both must be true
```javascript
// Show streak badge if: logged in AND streak is long enough
if (isLoggedIn && streakDays >= 7) {
  showStreakBadge();
}
```

**`||` (OR)** — At least one must be true
```javascript
// Show welcome screen if: new user OR hasn't logged in today
if (isNewUser || !hasLoggedInToday) {
  showWelcomeScreen();
}
```

**`!` (NOT)** — Flips true to false and vice versa
```javascript
if (!isLoggedIn) {
  // redirect to login
  window.location.href = '/login';
}
```

**Combining all three:**
```javascript
// Show upgrade prompt if: not premium AND (streak >= 30 OR more than 100 habits)
if (!isPremium && (streakDays >= 30 || totalHabits > 100)) {
  showUpgradePrompt();
}
```

When an if/else just assigns one of two values, there's a shorter syntax:

```javascript
// Long form:
let message;
if (isLoggedIn) {
  message = 'Welcome back!';
} else {
  message = 'Please log in.';
}

// Ternary form:
const message = isLoggedIn ? 'Welcome back!' : 'Please log in.';
```

Syntax: `condition ? valueIfTrue : valueIfFalse`

**When to use ternary:**
- Simple value assignment (like above)
- Inside JSX/templates: `{isLoggedIn ? <Dashboard /> : <Login />}`

**When NOT to use ternary:**
- When you have multiple actions (not just one value)
- When the condition is complex
- Nested ternaries are almost always harder to read than if/else

### The `for` loop — for a known number of repetitions:
```javascript
// Count from 1 to 5
for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
  console.log('Day ' + i);
}
// Output:
// Day 1
// Day 2
// Day 3
// Day 4
// Day 5
```

The three parts: `for (start; condition; increment)`
- **start**: `let i = 1` — begin at 1
- **condition**: `i <= 5` — keep going while this is true
- **increment**: `i++` — add 1 after each loop

### Looping over an array:
```javascript
const habits = ['Meditate', 'Exercise', 'Read', 'Journal'];

for (let i = 0; i < habits.length; i++) {
  console.log(`Habit ${i + 1}: ${habits[i]}`);
}
```

For arrays, modern JavaScript has cleaner alternatives to `for` loops:

**`forEach`** — Run code for each item (no return value)
```javascript
const habits = ['Meditate', 'Exercise', 'Read'];

habits.forEach((habit) => {
  console.log(`✓ ${habit}`);
});
// ✓ Meditate
// ✓ Exercise
// ✓ Read
```

**`map`** — Transform each item, create a new array
```javascript
const habits = ['Meditate', 'Exercise', 'Read'];

const withEmoji = habits.map((habit) => `🎯 ${habit}`);
console.log(withEmoji);
// ['🎯 Meditate', '🎯 Exercise', '🎯 Read']
```

**Key difference:** `forEach` does something with each item. `map` transforms each item into something else and gives you a new array.

Two more array methods you'll use daily:

**`filter`** — Keep only items that pass a test
```javascript
const habits = [
  { name: 'Meditate', completed: true },
  { name: 'Exercise', completed: false },
  { name: 'Read', completed: true },
];

const completedHabits = habits.filter((h) => h.completed);
// [{ name: 'Meditate', completed: true }, { name: 'Read', completed: true }]

const pendingHabits = habits.filter((h) => !h.completed);
// [{ name: 'Exercise', completed: false }]
```

**`find`** — Get the first item that matches
```javascript
const meditateHabit = habits.find((h) => h.name === 'Meditate');
// { name: 'Meditate', completed: true }

const notExist = habits.find((h) => h.name === 'Yoga');
// undefined (returns undefined if nothing found)
```

A **function** is a named, reusable block of code. You define it once, call it many times.

Without functions:
```javascript
// File 1: Dashboard
const streakDays = Math.floor((Date.now() - lastHabitDate) / 86400000);
if (streakDays >= 7) badgeText = '🔥 On fire';
else if (streakDays >= 3) badgeText = '⚡ Getting there';
else badgeText = '📌 Just start';

// File 2: Profile page (same code repeated!)
const streakDays = Math.floor((Date.now() - lastHabitDate) / 86400000);
if (streakDays >= 7) badgeText = '🔥 On fire';
else if (streakDays >= 3) badgeText = '⚡ Getting there';
else badgeText = '📌 Just start';
```

With a function:
```javascript
// Defined once
function getStreakBadge(lastHabitDate) {
  const days = Math.floor((Date.now() - lastHabitDate) / 86400000);
  if (days >= 7) return '🔥 On fire';
  if (days >= 3) return '⚡ Getting there';
  return '📌 Just start';
}

// Called everywhere
const badge = getStreakBadge(user.lastHabitDate);
```

