contentSections.body:
```javascript
//     name     parameters (inputs)
//      ↓        ↓
function greetUser(name, isLoggedIn) {
  if (!isLoggedIn) {
    return 'Please log in first.';  // return exits the function
  }
  return `Welcome back, ${name}!`;
}           // ↑ return value (output)

// Calling the function:
const message = greetUser('Sarah', true);
console.log(message);  // 'Welcome back, Sarah!'

const error = greetUser('Sarah', false);
console.log(error);    // 'Please log in first.'
```

**Arrow function syntax** (modern, common in React):
```javascript
// Traditional
function add(a, b) {
  return a + b;
}

// Arrow function — identical behavior
const add = (a, b) => {
  return a + b;
};

// Arrow function — short form (one-liner)
const add = (a, b) => a + b;
```

**Create a function when:**
1. You're writing the same code more than once
2. A chunk of code does one clear thing (even if you only use it once)
3. You want to test a piece of logic in isolation

**Good function design:**
```javascript
// ✅ One job, clear name, returns one thing
function isValidEmail(email) {
  return email.includes('@') && email.includes('.');
}

// ✅ Clear inputs, predictable output
function formatDate(dateMs) {
  return new Date(dateMs).toLocaleDateString('en-US');
}

// ❌ Too many jobs in one function
function validateAndSaveAndEmailUser(user) {
  // validates user, saves to DB, sends email — 3 things!
  // hard to test, hard to reuse
}
```
